1 Introduction

1 . 1 M o t i v a t i o n

Raw data is found all around us and is being collected at an exponentially higher rate than ever before. In fact, at any point, 90% of the world’s data is generated ovewithin last two years [Dragland2013]. However, due to the sheer volume of data collected, much is left unused. In 1982, John Naisbitt famously stated: “We are drowning in information but starved for knowledge” in his book Megatrends [Naisbitt] which today, more than ever, holds true. The data t h a t g e t s u s e d t o s e e k i n s i g h t is often objective data ( i . e . r e p r e s e n t i n g f a c t s a n d n o t p e r s o n a l f e e l i n g s )lused f o r i n s t a n c e , for companies to develop business strategies, at hospitals in patient care and treatment, am or to improve a metric in one’s personal li eor this thesis we, suggest a different motivation for the collection and usage of data: collecting and visualizing data for social and experiential purposes. Specifically, our aim is to foster storytelling and shared reflection using subjective and personal data collected during joint experiences.

Personal tracking has gained traction since the early years of the new millennium [ W o l f, Swan, Choe] us, often combined with information visualizat toolsion to createteresting and easily understood visualizations [Ware] a n d r e c e n t l y, u s i n g data physicalization [Jansen. 2015However, self-tracking for experiential purposes has often been neglected in comparison to tracking to improve health or other aspects of life improvement [ C h o e ]. W h i l e research e x i s t s t h a t discuss e s the sociality of tracking [Rooksby, Maitland], i t f o c u s e s predominantly o n t h e s o c i a l a s p e c t s o f t r a c k i n g f o r the sake of motivating each other to improve performance . I n s t e a d , i n t h i s t h e s i s , w e investigat e the impact of tracking important moments together and how that affects the overalling experie of t h e s e co-present momentsc
